{{blpsources|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Lisa Graves | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = | alma_mater = [[Cornell Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor]]) | other_names = | occupation = Nonprofit executive, political activist | known_for = Former executive director of [[Center for Media and Democracy]] | movement = [[Progressivism in the United States|Progressivism]] }}
'''Lisa Graves''' is a [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] activist who is senior fellow and former executive director of the [[Center for Media and Democracy]] (CMD). She served in this role from 2009 to 2017, when she became president of True North Research and co-director of DocumentedInvestigations.org.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lisa Graves|url=https://www.influencewatch.org/person/lisa-graves/|website=Influence Watch|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Liberal Research Group May Settle Open Records Case |url=http://www.wpr.org/liberal-research-group-may-settle-open-records-case |accessdate=June 13, 2014 |publisher=Wisconsin Public Radio |date=December 4, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714202055/http://www.wpr.org/liberal-research-group-may-settle-open-records-case |archivedate=July 14, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Overby |first1=Peter |title=Liberal Watchdog Group: 'Fix The Debt' Movement More Astroturf Than Grassroots |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2013/02/23/172761961/liberal-watchdog-group-fix-the-debt-movement-more-astroturf-than-grassroots |accessdate=June 13, 2014 |publisher=National Public Radio |date=February 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name=craver>{{cite news |last1=Craver |first1=Jack |title=Progressive watchdog group gets two big anonymous donations |url=http://host.madison.com/news/local/writers/jack_craver/progressive-watchdog-group-gets-two-big-anonymous-donations/article_fd110a62-5ea5-11e3-90ad-001a4bcf887a.html |accessdate=June 13, 2014 |publisher=Capital Times |date=December 7, 2013}}</ref> Graves also serves on the advisory board of UnKoch.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://capitalresearch.org/article/unclear-funding-part-1/|title=Unclear Funding for UnKoch: Campus Activists Create a Boogeyman|access-date=2018-06-08|language=en-US}}</ref>
==Career== Graves received her [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from Cornell Law School.<ref name=martell>{{cite web|url=http://host.madison.com/wsj/news/local/govt-and-politics/know-your-madisonian-lisa-graves-helps-raise-awareness-of-public/article_b9e37fe6-6261-11e1-bafb-0019bb2963f4.html|title=Know Your Madisonian: Lisa Graves helps raise awareness of public-opinion manipulation|author=Interviewed Chris Martell|date=1 March 2012|work=madison.com}}</ref> She previously served as the Chief Counsel for Nominations on the [[United States Senate Judiciary Committee]] under Senator [[Patrick Leahy]] (D-Vermont) and as Deputy Assistant Attorney General in the [[United States Department of Justice]] during the [[Clinton Administration]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Savage|first1=Charlie|title=Newest Spy Court Pick Is a Democrat but Not a Liberal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/21/us/roberts-varies-pattern-in-choice-for-spy-court.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|accessdate=13 June 2014|publisher=New York Times|date=2013-08-20}}</ref> Graves also worked as the Senior Legislative Strategist on national security issues for the [[American Civil Liberties Union]],<ref name=martell/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.exposedbycmd.org/author/lisa-graves/|title=Lisa Graves, Author at EXPOSEDbyCMD|website=EXPOSEDbyCMD|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-01}}</ref> and as an adjunct professor at the [[George Washington University Law School]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.topwonks.org/experts/lisa-graves/|title=Lisa Graves - TopWonks|website=www.topwonks.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref>
Graves joined the progressive watchdog group [[Center for Media and Democracy]] in 2009 as executive director.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thedailypage.com/isthmus/article.php?article=36715 | title = Exposing ALEC: The Center for Media and Democracy goes after the right-wing powerhouse | publisher = [[Isthmus (newspaper)|Isthmus]] |date=May 10, 2012 |accessdate=June 26, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2012/04/exposing-alec-how-conservative-backed-state-laws-are-all-connected/255869/ |title=Exposing ALEC: How Conservative-Backed State Laws Are All Connected| publisher = [[The Atlantic]] |date=April 4, 2012 |accessdate=June 26, 2012}}</ref> Graves has investigated and reported on the [[Koch family|Koch Brothers]], the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]], and the [[State Policy Network]].
In 2012, Graves was interviewed about the Center for Media and Democracy project "ALEC Exposed" for the [[Bill Moyers]] documentary film ''United States of ALEC.''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://billmoyers.com/segment/united-states-of-alec/|title=United States of ALEC|last=Moyers|first=Bill|date=September 28, 2012|work=Moyers & Company|publisher=Public Affairs Television|authorlink=Bill Moyers|accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref>
In 2016, Graves was interviewed in [[Ava DuVernay]]'s documentary [[13th (film)|13th]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Abdullah|first=Melina|authorlink=Melina Abdullah|title=13th|date=2016-10-07|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5895028/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|last2=Alexander|last3=Booker|last4=Canales|first2=Michelle|first3=Cory|first4=Dolores|accessdate=2017-03-02}}</ref>
