{{for|the French Olympic athlete|Raymond Lefebvre (athlete)}}
[[File:Lefebvre, Raymond (Le Journal 1925).jpg|right|thumb|Raymond Lefebvre]]
'''Raymond'''-Louis '''Lefebvre''' ([[Vire]], 1891-Barents Sea, 1920) was a [[French people|French]] writer and political activist. He attended the [[2nd World Congress of the Comintern]] in 1920, but disappeared in the [[Barents Sea]] whilst returning.

Lefebvre served as a soldier during the [[First World War]] and in 1917 described his experiences in ''Le sacrifice d'Abraham'' (The Sacrifice of Abraham). He had been wounded and was revolted by the whole experience. This work placed him alongside [[Henri Barbusse]], [[Georges Duhamel]], [[Marcel Martinet]] – amongst others – as being one of the writers who developed a revolutionary perspective during the war.<ref name="Serge">{{cite journal|last1=Serge|first1=Victor|title=Héros et martyrs du communisme Raymond Lefebvre|journal=Le bulletin communiste|date=1921|volume=2|issue=4|url=https://www.marxists.org/francais/serge/works/1921/04/lefebvre.htm|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref> He was involved in setting up a radical veterans association, the [[Association Républicaine des Anciens Combattants]].<ref name="Serge"/>

After attending the 2nd Congress of the Cominiern, he was appointed to the Provisional International Bureau of the [[Kultintern]], an organisation set up to promote proletarian culture.<ref name="AB & Kultiintern">{{cite web|last1=Biggart|first1=John|title=Alexander Bogdanov and the short history of the Kultintern|url=https://bogdanovlibrary.org/current-research/|website=Alexander Bogdanov Library|publisher=Historical Materialism|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref> 

